<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920220-0087</DOCNO><DOCID>920220-0087.</DOCID><HL>   Shawmut Ex-Officer Pleads   Guilty to Embezzlement</HL><DATE>02/20/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   SNC</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>EASTERN U.S. BANKS (BAE)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   BOSTON -- A former senior vice president of ShawmutNational Corp.'s Shawmut Bank pleaded guilty in federal courtto embezzling more than $2.5 million from the bank, the U.S.Attorney's Office said.   Peter J. Regan, 48 years old, who managed therestructuring of troubled loans and the sale of seizedassets, was accused of funneling into his personal accountsmoney from some of the bank's debtors under his review, U.S.attorneys said.</LP><TEXT>   The accounts were set up in Boston, New Hampshire, Floridaand Switzerland under fictitious names. Money was diverted toaccounts from November 1987 to July 1991, when a wiretransfer totaling $580,000 to a Florida account wasdiscovered.   Mr. Regan was subsequently fired. The bank, which isseeking restitution, has recovered some of the money.   U.S. District Court Judge A. David Mazzone scheduledsentencing for April 21. Mr. Regan could be sentenced to fiveto 30 years in prison and fined $250,000 to $1 million foreach of the 55 counts to which he has pleaded guilty.</TEXT></DOC>